      • getUserIdentity

        public List<UserIdentity> getUserIdentity()
        Gets the value of the userIdentity property.

        This accessor method returns a reference to the live list, not a snapshot. Therefore any modification you make to the returned list will be present inside the JAXB object. This is why there is not a set method for the userIdentity property.

        For example, to add a new item, do as follows: 

            getUserIdentity().add(newItem);

        Objects of the following type(s) are allowed in the list UserIdentity

      • getDiskOrMemoryOrSwap

        public List<Object> getDiskOrMemoryOrSwap()
        Gets the value of the diskOrMemoryOrSwap property.

        This accessor method returns a reference to the live list, not a snapshot. Therefore any modification you make to the returned list will be present inside the JAXB object. This is why there is not a set method for the diskOrMemoryOrSwap property.

            getDiskOrMemoryOrSwap().add(newItem);

        Objects of the following type(s) are allowed in the list Disk Memory Swap Network TimeDuration TimeInstant ServiceLevel

      • getWallDurationOrCpuDurationOrNodeCount

        public List<Object> getWallDurationOrCpuDurationOrNodeCount()
        Gets the value of the wallDurationOrCpuDurationOrNodeCount property.

        This accessor method returns a reference to the live list, not a snapshot. Therefore any modification you make to the returned list will be present inside the JAXB object. This is why there is not a set method for the wallDurationOrCpuDurationOrNodeCount property.

        For example, to add a new item, do as follows: 

            getWallDurationOrCpuDurationOrNodeCount().add(newItem);

        Objects of the following type(s) are allowed in the list WallDuration CpuDuration NodeCount Processors EndTime StartTime MachineName SubmitHost Queue ProjectName Host PhaseResource VolumeResource ResourceType ConsumableResourceType
